s=3D"fusion-content-tb fusion-content-tb-1"><p>In any working environment, =
there are various instances where you would be required to calculate the du=
ration between two dates.</p>
<p>A human resource officer would need to know how long a given employee ha=
s worked with the company or the actual age of the various employees for pl=
anning purposes. In an automotive industry, you would need to compute how l=
ong, say a given vehicle has taken to be serviced. For most NGOs, it would =
be needful to know, based on the contractual terms of various consultants, =
how many months/years are remaining and subsequently, how many employees ha=
ve their contracts ending, say in the next 3 months, 6 months, and so on.</=
p>
<p>There are many ways that you can achieve to calculate the difference bet=
ween any two dates in Excel.</p>
<p>For this example, we shall discuss how to calculate the length of servic=
e of various employees as at a given date, but the concept applies in all t=
he scenarios described above.</p>
<h2 data-fontsize=3D"28" style=3D"--fontSize: 28; line-height: 1.5;" data-l=
ineheight=3D"42px" class=3D"fusion-responsive-typography-calculated"><stron=
g>Calculate the duration of service of employees</strong></h2>
<p>We have the following subset of data extract.</p>
<p><img fetchpriority=3D"high" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-f=
ull wp-image-32449" src=3D"https://datacycleanalytics.com/wp-content/upload=
s/2018/03/1.png" alt=3D"" width=3D"383" height=3D"277"></p>
<p>In cell C2 we shall type a date as at which we shall compute the length =
of service. This can be (1) a date that you hardcode, or (2) a date represe=
nting today=E2=80=99s date, or (3) a formula that returns the end of the pr=
evious month with reference to today=E2=80=99s date.</p>
<p>To always use the current (i.e. today=E2=80=99s) date, type the followin=
g in cell C2:</p>
<p><strong>=3DTODAY( )</strong></p>
<p>The Excel=E2=80=99s TODAY function will always return the current date.<=
/p>
<p>To always use the end of the previous month with reference to today=E2=
=80=99s date, we shall type the following in C2:</p>
<p><strong>=3DEOMONTH (TODAY( ), -1)</strong></p>
<p>The EOMONTH function normally returns a serial number that represents th=
e end of the month, =E2=80=9Cx=E2=80=9D number of months before or after th=
e specified date. The number of months before or after can be a positive nu=
mber or a negative number or zero if you want to return the end of the curr=
ent month. For instance, if the TODAY function wrapped inside this formula =
is assumed to be =E2=80=9C8/8/2017=E2=80=9D then using 0 as the last parame=
ter will result in =E2=80=9C31/8/2017=E2=80=9D, using -2 will return =E2=80=
=9C30/6/2017=E2=80=9D whereas using a +4 will yield =E2=80=9C31/12/2017=E2=
=80=9D</p>
<p>In this example, we shall enter this EOMONTH function in cell C2 to alwa=
ys consider the end of the previous month.</p>
<h2 data-fontsize=3D"28" style=3D"--fontSize: 28; line-height: 1.5;" data-l=
ineheight=3D"42px" class=3D"fusion-responsive-typography-calculated"><stron=
g>Different approaches to compute differences between two dates</strong></h=
2>
<p>Let us explore various methods to calculate the duration between two dat=
es.</p>
<h3 data-fontsize=3D"18" style=3D"--fontSize: 18; line-height: 1.5; --minFo=
ntSize: 18;" data-lineheight=3D"27px" class=3D"fusion-responsive-typography=
-calculated"><strong><em>Method 1: Subtract the two dates</em></strong></h3=
>
<p>The obvious method I have seen with various trainees is to subtract the =
date of joining from the specified end date and then divide the resultant v=
alue by 365 (or 360 for other regions) as shown below.</p>
<p><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp-image-32450" src=
=3D"https://datacycleanalytics.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/2.png" alt=3D=
"" width=3D"534" height=3D"189"></p>
<p>The equivalent of the formula shown in cell E5 above would be <strong>=
=3D DAYS ($C$2, D6)/365</strong> which would give similar results.</p>
<h3 data-fontsize=3D"18" style=3D"--fontSize: 18; line-height: 1.5; --minFo=
ntSize: 18;" data-lineheight=3D"27px" class=3D"fusion-responsive-typography=
-calculated"><strong><em>Method 2: Subtract the years</em></strong></h3>
<p>In this approach, we assume we just need to compute the difference betwe=
en the two dates as whole years, as is the case when you want to compute yo=
ur age as at the last birthday.</p>
<p>We therefore employ the formula shown in the figure below.</p>
<p><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp-image-32451" src=
=3D"https://datacycleanalytics.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/3.png" alt=3D=
"" width=3D"539" height=3D"191"></p>
<p>This approach rounds the result to the nearest whole number.</p>
<h3 data-fontsize=3D"18" style=3D"--fontSize: 18; line-height: 1.5; --minFo=
ntSize: 18;" data-lineheight=3D"27px" class=3D"fusion-responsive-typography=
-calculated"><strong><em>Method 3: Using the YEARFRAC function</em></strong=
></h3>
<p>This method gives similar results with the first method above. That is, =
it will compute the <em>fractional year differences</em> between two dates.=
</p>
<p>For instance, if the last day is =E2=80=9C31/07/2017=E2=80=9D and you jo=
ined the company on =E2=80=9C27/09/1998=E2=80=9D then the formula will comp=
ute the difference taking into account differential months. So, whereas met=
hod 2 would give 19 as the difference in years, YEARFRAC will yield 18.84.<=
/p>
<p>Take a look.</p>
<p><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp-image-32452" src=
=3D"https://datacycleanalytics.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/4.png" alt=3D=
"" width=3D"540" height=3D"189"></p>
<p>Notice that in this case you start by specifying the date of joining in =
the formula.</p>
<h2 data-fontsize=3D"28" style=3D"--fontSize: 28; line-height: 1.5;" data-l=
ineheight=3D"42px" class=3D"fusion-responsive-typography-calculated"><stron=
g>Let us compare the results</strong></h2>
<p>The figure that follows compares the output of the various approaches di=
scussed so far.</p>
<p><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp-image-32453" src=
=3D"https://datacycleanalytics.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/5.png" alt=3D=
"" width=3D"618" height=3D"189"></p>
<h3 data-fontsize=3D"18" style=3D"--fontSize: 18; line-height: 1.5; --minFo=
ntSize: 18;" data-lineheight=3D"27px" class=3D"fusion-responsive-typography=
-calculated"><strong><em>Method 4: Using DATEDIF function</em></strong></h3=
>
<p>When you type DATEDIF as you would do with any other formulas, this form=
ula doesn=E2=80=99t show a prompt (normally called the intellisense) as oth=
er formulas do. It was popular in earlier Excel versions 2003 and earlier) =
but has since not been given a lot of focus. I guess Microsoft might stop s=
upporting it very soon (my guess).</p>
<p>This function computes the difference in either the <strong>completed/fu=
ll</strong> years, months or days, between two dates. Just like the YEARFRA=
C function, it also requires you to specify the starting and the ending dat=
e. However, you would need to specify the time unit of output, in terms of =
<em>years, months</em> or <em>days</em>.</p>
<p>Syntax: <strong>DATEDIF (Start_date, End_date, Unit)</strong></p>
<p>There are six different outputs that you can get based on the time unit =
you specify as follows:[/vc_column_text][gem_table]
</p><table style=3D"width: 100%;">
<thead>
<tr style=3D"height: 10px;">
<th style=3D"height: 10px;">
<h6 data-fontsize=3D"12" style=3D"--fontSize: 12; line-height: 1.2; --minFo=
ntSize: 12;" data-lineheight=3D"14.4px" class=3D"fusion-responsive-typograp=
hy-calculated">Unit</h6>
</th>
<th style=3D"height: 10px;">
<h6 data-fontsize=3D"12" style=3D"--fontSize: 12; line-height: 1.2; --minFo=
ntSize: 12;" data-lineheight=3D"14.4px" class=3D"fusion-responsive-typograp=
hy-calculated">Output</h6>
</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr style=3D"height: 22px;">
<td style=3D"height: 22px;">=E2=80=9Cy=E2=80=9D</td>
<td style=3D"height: 22px;">Difference in terms of complete years</td>
</tr>
<tr style=3D"height: 22px;">
<td style=3D"height: 22px;">=E2=80=9Cm=E2=80=9D</td>
<td style=3D"height: 22px;">Difference in terms of complete months</td>
</tr>
<tr style=3D"height: 22px;">
<td style=3D"height: 22px;">=E2=80=9Cd=E2=80=9D</td>
<td style=3D"height: 22px;">Difference in terms of complete days</td>
</tr>
<tr style=3D"height: 88px;">
<td style=3D"height: 88px;">=E2=80=9Cyd=E2=80=9D</td>
<td style=3D"height: 88px;">Returns the difference of complete days, ignori=
ng the ones in the years that have been completed. Simply put, for the spec=
ified start date, it takes the equivalent date in the immediate previous ye=
ar as the basis of subtracting the completed days</td>
</tr>
<tr style=3D"height: 66px;">
<td style=3D"height: 66px;">=E2=80=9Cym=E2=80=9D</td>
<td style=3D"height: 66px;">Returns the difference of complete months, igno=
ring the ones in the years that have been completed. It takes the immediate=
 previous year as the basis of subtracting the full months</td>
</tr>
<tr style=3D"height: 66px;">
<td style=3D"height: 66px;">=E2=80=9Cmd=E2=80=9D</td>
<td style=3D"height: 66px;">This interval just subtracts the day part of th=
e two dates. For instance, in the table below, notice the =E2=80=9Cmd=E2=80=
=9D column is the difference between the day element of the two dates. In r=
ow 9 for example it is 31-1=3D30</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>The figure below illustrates all the six possible outputs.</p>
<p><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp-image-32454" src=
=3D"https://datacycleanalytics.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6.png" alt=3D=
"" width=3D"544" height=3D"303"></p>
<h2 data-fontsize=3D"28" style=3D"--fontSize: 28; line-height: 1.5;" data-l=
ineheight=3D"42px" class=3D"fusion-responsive-typography-calculated"><stron=
g>In conclusion</strong></h2>
<p>The various approaches discussed above are enough arsenals for various s=
cenarios you may encounter. Should you have comments or questions regarding=
 manipulating dates in Excel, please lodge them in the comments area below.=
</p>
